<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-307-084  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 307 084.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 26 1990 v4 n12 p18(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Agencies fear new FIRMR may reduce buying power. (FederalInformation Resources Management Regulation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smithmidford, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The General Services Administration (GSA) has released for commentSubchapter C of its Federal Information Resources ManagementRegulation (FIRMR) improvement effort, a project aimed atreorganizing and simplifying rules for purchase and management ofcomputers, communications equipment, and records.andP;  Subchapter Cincludes a proposal for a $2.5 million ceiling for agencypurchases of computer equipment, support services, and software.andO;Agencies and vendors are calling on the GSA to lift this limit,which they say would lower agencies' buying authority.andP;  SubchapterD of the GSA's revised FIRMR includes a proposal to free agenciesfrom justifying purchases of only new computers.andP;  Theused-computer industry has complained about this provision, andthe GSA has been asked to clarify and justify it.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyPolicyGovernment RegulationPurchasesComputer SystemsEnd UsersVendorsUnited States. General Services Administration.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>